WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.280
Hi, my name is Darren Airey, and today I'd like to talk about why you should add logging

00:00:09.280 --> 00:00:13.120
to your code, and hopefully how to make it more helpful.

00:00:13.120 --> 00:00:17.680
We have in production Shiny apps, Plumber APIs, and R Markdowns.

00:00:17.680 --> 00:00:22.080
I work in the insurance industry, and so for example, we have a Plumber API that helps

00:00:22.080 --> 00:00:23.959
price insurance policies.

00:00:23.959 --> 00:00:26.440
So if something goes wrong, we need to know about it right away.

00:00:27.400 --> 00:00:31.480
So when we get something like this in our Markdown that runs hourly, it gets a little

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:32.480
annoying.

00:00:32.480 --> 00:00:33.919
What is this error?

00:00:33.919 --> 00:00:34.919
How do we fix it?

00:00:34.919 --> 00:00:38.400
It'd be nice to have some helpful hints to help you understand what happened, and maybe

00:00:38.400 --> 00:00:43.520
some convenient ways of getting notified when this error happens.

00:00:43.520 --> 00:00:46.840
So when you're going through your code, it's kind of like walking in a dark forest, and

00:00:46.840 --> 00:00:49.160
you're not sure exactly where you're going.

00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:53.639
But by including some type of logging, you can have these trail markers that are on trees,

00:00:54.160 --> 00:00:59.320
so you have some sense of idea of where you're going, and how to troubleshoot your code.

00:00:59.320 --> 00:01:02.279
So to demonstrate logging, I have a simple Plumber API.

00:01:02.279 --> 00:01:04.000
We're just going to divide some numbers.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:07.239
We have A as a numerator, and B as a denominator.

00:01:07.239 --> 00:01:12.120
And then for example, we do 100 by 4, we're going to get 25 as a result.

00:01:12.120 --> 00:01:17.559
So to add our first trail marker, we're going to use the log4r here as a demonstration purpose.

00:01:17.559 --> 00:01:21.919
We're going to define the logger object, and then below we have an informational message

00:01:21.959 --> 00:01:24.959
that says, attempting to divide A by B.

00:01:24.959 --> 00:01:28.639
So now when we run through this example again, we're going to see in our console,

00:01:28.639 --> 00:01:31.279
info attempting to divide 100 by 4.

00:01:31.279 --> 00:01:33.279
So that's kind of useful.

00:01:33.279 --> 00:01:35.680
So we're going to add a second trail marker here.

00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:39.959
What if we want to know when somebody does not include an input?

00:01:39.959 --> 00:01:43.639
We want to be notified of that, so we're going to include a warning message here.

00:01:43.639 --> 00:01:48.680
So when there's no inputs in the numerator or denominator, the user is going to receive

00:01:48.680 --> 00:01:51.720
back a must apply numerator or denominator.

00:01:51.720 --> 00:01:55.680
And in our console, we're going to see this warning message with the same message.

00:01:55.680 --> 00:01:59.480
That's interesting, but only you are going to see this message.

00:01:59.480 --> 00:02:04.800
No one else that you care about is going to see this and be notified when this error happens.

00:02:04.800 --> 00:02:09.440
So we need to go beyond these trail markers on trees, and you have some type of satellite

00:02:09.440 --> 00:02:13.960
communicator capability to let people know when these types of things happen.

00:02:13.960 --> 00:02:18.559
When I go hiking by myself, I have a satellite communication device like this to let my wife

00:02:18.559 --> 00:02:26.600
know where and when I'm at all times, so she can feel at ease when I'm doing things like this.

00:02:26.600 --> 00:02:32.160
So if you want to add satellite communicator capability to your logging, there's a bunch

00:02:32.160 --> 00:02:37.839
of sources available, Azure, Amazon Web Services, and Google Cloud all have their own type of

00:02:37.839 --> 00:02:43.160
logging service available where you can send your OS log file directly or interact with

00:02:43.160 --> 00:02:45.960
the logging system with an API.

00:02:45.960 --> 00:02:51.320
So to add satellite communication ability to our example, we're just going to modify

00:02:51.320 --> 00:02:58.000
the logger and add a syslog appender, and we're going to call it division calculator API.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:02:59.000
What's syslog?

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:04.240
Well, syslog is on a Linux system, the system's primary logging file.

00:03:04.240 --> 00:03:08.520
You see a bunch of syslog files here, and in that syslog, you're going to see a bunch

00:03:08.520 --> 00:03:12.360
of random stuff in there that you don't really care about, but you're also going to see your

00:03:12.360 --> 00:03:17.639
output for, in this case, division calculator API must supply a numerator and denominator.

00:03:17.639 --> 00:03:21.199
So now there's a source file that's being written to.

00:03:21.199 --> 00:03:27.160
So what we have, an organization, we have our plumber, Shiny applications, and it's

00:03:27.160 --> 00:03:32.000
all hosted on a Posit Connect instance on our virtual machine running Linux, and then

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:36.000
all that is writing to our syslog file.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:40.000
And we have it integrated with Azure Monitor, so all those syslog files get uploaded to

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:44.880
the cloud, and now, when you go to a web browser, you can conveniently see in your

00:03:44.880 --> 00:03:49.279
syslog table where process name equals division calculator API.

00:03:49.279 --> 00:03:53.039
So now you see all those messages, and if you wanted to, you can filter it out so you

00:03:53.039 --> 00:03:57.600
don't see the informational messages, you just see the warnings, and you can even set

00:03:57.600 --> 00:04:03.039
up alerts so you know when those things happen and get notified by email or if you really

00:04:03.039 --> 00:04:05.800
want to, by text messages.

00:04:05.800 --> 00:04:08.240
Maybe not everyone wants to do that.

00:04:08.240 --> 00:04:11.919
But I hope from this talk you can see that when you have your code, it's kind of like

00:04:11.919 --> 00:04:12.919
walking in a dark forest.

00:04:12.919 --> 00:04:17.359
You really don't know where you are, but by including logging, you have a better sense

00:04:17.359 --> 00:04:22.559
of where things could go wrong, and by using a cloud monitoring solution, it's like having

00:04:22.559 --> 00:04:27.079
a satellite communication device to let people know what's going on.

00:04:27.079 --> 00:04:31.160
I'd love to talk more about logging, but you can use this QR code in this link below to

00:04:31.160 --> 00:04:34.839
learn more about it, and if any of these things resonate with you, let's chat.

00:04:34.839 --> 00:04:35.600
Thanks so much.

00:04:35.799 --> 00:04:36.299
Bye-bye.

